    riskFactors: ["Uncertain maternal dates or late prenatal care", "Discrepancy between estimated and actual gestational age", "Small for gestational age or large for gestational age infants", "Maternal substance abuse affecting fetal development", "Multiple gestation pregnancies", "Preterm birth requiring accurate age determination for treatment protocols"],
    diagnostics: ["Perform New Ballard Score within 12-96 hours after birth for greatest accuracy", "Evaluate six neuromuscular criteria: posture, square window, arm recoil, popliteal angle, scarf sign, heel to ear", "Evaluate six physical maturity criteria: skin, lanugo, plantar surface, breast, eye/ear, genitalia", "Sum scores from both categories (-10 to 50 points) and correlate to gestational age (20-44 weeks)", "Document and compare with obstetric dating for consistency", "Classify infant as appropriate, small, or large for gestational age using growth curves"],
    management: ["Determine appropriate level of neonatal care based on assessed gestational age", "Initiate feeding protocols matched to neuromuscular maturity (gavage vs breastfeeding)", "Implement thermoregulation interventions appropriate to gestational age", "Establish ventilatory support expectations based on pulmonary maturity assessment", "Adjust medication dosing protocols to corrected gestational age", "Screen for gestational-age-specific complications (RDS, NEC, IVH for preterm)"],
    nursingActions: ["Perform assessment during a quiet alert state when possible for accurate neuromuscular evaluation", "Document each criterion score individually along with total score", "Communicate gestational age to the interdisciplinary team for care planning", "Assess posture by observing infant in supine position without stimulation", "Measure square window angle by flexing the wrist toward the forearm", "Test arm recoil by extending both arms alongside the body and releasing", "Evaluate scarf sign by drawing arm across chest toward opposite shoulder"],
